- Pull it under.
- Pull it under.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:57.040
I want the children to learn

00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:58.760
without knowing
that they're actually learning.

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:01.480
So I think if you make the lesson
really fun and enjoyable,

00:05:01.560 --> 00:05:04.960
they forget that they're learning and
they just do it without thinking.

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:06.600
George!

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:09.720
Now using our rap, what's
the next thing we've got to do?

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:11.360
Two lines, two lines.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.680
Two lines, two lines.
Let's put two lines, two lines in.

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:18.560
The success criteria
we developed together as a class

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:20.360
and we looked at column addition

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:23.080
and then we wrote lists
on a step-by-step guide

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:24.600
on how to achieve that.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:28.080
Add the right, then add the left.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:32.920
That's to tell you that
first of all you add the units...

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Once we'd done that
we've simplified it

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:38.120
and then the children
created their own actions

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:39.840
and their own rap to go with it.

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.200
Boing, 10s over

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:47.320
because you have to put the 10...

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:49.080
And if they've got a little routine
or a little rap,

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.120
then it can help them
work out what the next step is

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:55.560
and just make it a bit easier
for them to get through their work

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:56.920
rather than panic, I think.

